I have just updated the code to allow for concurrent execution. It is also possible to nest `ParallelChain`s inside other `ParallelChain`s, all executing concurrently, such as the following
```
num_child_chains = 3

input_variables = ["input1", "input2"]

chain_concurrent = ParallelChain(
    input_variables=input_variables,
    chains={
        f"output{i}": ParallelChain(
            input_variables=input_variables,
            chains={
                f"output{i}_{j}": FakeChain(
                    input_variables=input_variables,
                    output_variables=[f"chain_out{i}_{j}"],
                    chain_id=i * num_child_chains + j,
                )
                for j in range(num_child_chains)
            },
            concurrent=True,
        )
        for i in range(num_child_chains)
    },
    concurrent=True,
)
```

See documentation in the PR for a full example. In order to add support for nested concurrent `ParallelChain`s, I needed to implement this with `concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor` rather than using `asyncio` because `asyncio` [does not allow for nested event loops](https://bugs.python.org/issue22239).

Furthermore, I have added support for multiple outputs per child chain, such that the top-level `ParallelChain`'s output flattens the keys of its children's output as follows:
```
{
    'output_for_chain_1/chain_1_output_1': str, 'output_for_chain_1/chain_1_output_2': str, ... },
    'output_for_chain_2/chain_2_output_1': str, 'output_for_chain_2/chain_2_output_2': str, ... },
}
```

